creased significantly at the second assessment relative to the first (0.012 Ã¯Â¿Â½ 0.012 vs. 0.418 Ã¯Â¿Â½ 0.302; P &lt; 0.0004) (Fig. 1). No such change was observed in those randomized to placebo (0.009 Ã¯Â¿Â½ 0.010 vs. 0.017 Ã¯Â¿Â½ 0.015; P = NS). Of those receiving bupropion, 46% (6/13) were phenotypically poor metabolizers after treatment.&quot;


